 the path to radicalization is a nuanced process of moving in and out of far-right scenes throughout adolescence and adulthood.Hate in the Homeland is essential for understanding the tactics and underlying ideas of modern far-right extremism. This eye-opening book takes readers into the mainstream places and spaces where today's far right is engaging and ensnaring young people, and reveals innovative strategies we can use to combat extremist radicalization.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 10. Jan 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  a14 words.  aAryan Nations.  aBring the War Home.  aCas Mudde.  aDavid Lane.  aDavid Myatt.  aGreat Replacement.  aHitler.  aKathleen Belew.  aPewDiePie.  aSouthern Poverty Law Center.  aThe Far Right Today.  aThe White Power Movement and Paramilitary America.  aalt right.  aalt-right.  aanti-Semitism.  acombatting extremism.  adomestic extremism.  aextremist identities.  afourteen words.  amainstreaming of extremism.  amodern far right.  aneo-Nazi.  anormalization of extremism.  aonline radicalization.  arace war.  aracism.  aviolence.  awhite nationalism.  awhite supremacist extremism.  awhite supremacy.  ayouth radicalization.40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691234298423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691234298/original  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK